### Description

Angular v19 - using standalone

Currently I develop a service called AuthService and added it to the global provider (yes, i don't intend to use @Inject({providedin:'root'}, but don't need to know why, as this is not the crux).
However I notice that if the AuthService  has a constructor that need to be injected with something (e.g HttpClient instance), I still need to apply @Injectable().   

```
@Injectable() <==this annotation has to be added in order for the DI to work on its constructor.
export class AuthService {
    private readonly http ;

    constructor(hc:HttpClient  ){
       this.http = hc;
    }
```

### Proposed solution

if a custom service has already been added to the provider, its constructor should be implicitly be able to be injected with another service via its constructor by default, rather than force developer to apply @Injectable() . This align with Angular goal of reducing boilerplate.
In other word, @Injectable can be applied implicitly if the service already added to the providers.

Of course, a flag can be added to the angular.json to enable or disable such implicit, for purpose of migration.



